Prolog
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair streaked with blue. A girl meant weakness to the Ice King. Up until this point, he had only produced sons.
You have two choices: either you kill the child or you send her into the wilderness. That is your punishment for your failure, Eirwen," he spat out her name as if it were poisonous. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always one kingdom. Formerly, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. In the North lay the non-magical kingdom, in the South a kingdom full of fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and there was an endless war between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
Die Verzweiflung im Süden war so groß, dass die königliche Familie zum allem bereit war, um das Blutvergießen zu beenden. Sie boten an, ihre einzige Prinzessin als Königin in den Norden zu entsenden, wo sie einen Sohn, den künftigen König, gebären sollte. In diesem Fall würde sich der Norden mit dem Süden zu einem Königreich vereinen. Der Norden nahm den Vorschlag an und Prinzessin Eirwen heiratete Prinz Akull.
„Ich bitte Euch, mein König, macht mit mir, was Ihr wollt, sperrt mich ein, verbannt mich oder tötet mich, aber verschont mein Kind“, flehte Königin Eirwen, mit ihrem Kind in den Armen.
Der Eiskönig schaute voller Abscheu auf seine Königin herab. Vielleicht, aber nur vielleicht, würde er Erbarmen mit ihr haben. Mit der Frau, mit der er seit 22 Jahren verheiratet war, die ihm in seinen schlimmsten Zeiten beigestanden und die ihm seine Söhne geschenkt hatte.
„Na gut. Das Kind kann im Palast bleiben“, sagte er, was von der Königin mit einem Seufzer zur Kenntnis genommen wurde. „Aber“, fügte er hinzu, „du wirst hingerichtet.“
Der königliche Berater und Königin Eirwen sahen sich entsetzt an. Langsam wandte sie ihren Blick zum Boden. „Ja, mein König.“ Sie verneigte sich.
The Ice King instructed the royal advisor to bring the Queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's free rooms. Then, he ordered the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution platform, where all the city's citizens could watch.
As the guards escorted her to the execution platform, there was a loud commotion among the citizens as they realized that their only, beloved Queen would be executed. Some people wept, others shouted and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this was happening, but everyone was in agreement.
"Let her go free!"
"Why do you do this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Executioner. The woman who had been Queen would be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how Queen Eirwen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then the executioner ignited the wooden stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Do not give up, Kari." This marked the end of Queen Eirwen's regency.
Total silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room located farthest to the left in the southern wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants passing by wondered what was inside that room and were afraid of it. Rumors were circulating among the maidservants in the palace. It was said that the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room and waiting to be released.
Her assumption could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed towards the southern wing, while the servants walked around whispering to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors also concerned Ivory, as she was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Tap, tap. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" Ivory whispered outside the door intricately decorated with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if, unlike the last attempt, entry would actually be granted this time. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory giggled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book against Ivory's shoulder but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock came from inside, presumably to confirm her presence. Where else could she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. Previously, Ivory had entered without asking.
Aus dem Inneren vernahm Ivory ein Klopfen. Das bedeutete wohl ein „Ja“. Die Kälte und das Geräusch ließen Ivory erschauern. Es fühlte sich komisch an, ein Geräusch aus einem angeblich leeren Zimmer zu hören, obwohl Ivory schon seit einigen Jahren dort hineinging.
„Ich komme rein“, sagte Ivory und öffnete langsam die Tür. Der Anblick, der sich Ivory in dem Raum bot, war für normale Menschen ungewöhnlich, kam für Ivory aber nicht unerwartet. Überall lag Papier. Bücher waren verstreut, der Schreibtisch war zerbrochen und mehrere Eisskulpturen lagen herum. Es gab keine Fenster und wenig bis gar kein Licht. Außerdem war es kälter als im restlichen Palast (was schon einiges sagte). Der Raum sah aus, als sei ein Schneesturm hindurch gefegt.
Das Mädchen lag zusammengerollt in ihrem Bett, eingewickelt in ihre Bettdecke, und las in einem ihrer Notizbücher. Eine kleine Laterne erhellte den Raum.
„Welches Notizbuch ist das?“, fragte Ivory und setzte sich neben Kari aufs Bett.
